%S A395772 1,3,2,6,4,6,8,12,6,12,11,12,14,24,8,24,18,18,20,24,16,33,22,24,20,42,
%T A395772 18,48,30,24,30,48,22,54,32,36,36,60,28,48,42,48,44,66,24,66,46,48,56,
%U A395772 60,36,84,52,54,44,96,40,90,58,48,62,90,48,96,56,66,66,108,44,96
%N A395772 The twisted Euler phi-function for the Dirichlet character kronecker(-11,.) mod 11.
%C A395772 We have h(-11*n^2), the class number of the order of Z[(1+sqrt(-11))/2] with discriminant -11*n^2, is equal to a(n).
%C A395772 In general, let d < 0 be a fundamental discriminant and n be a positive integer such that d*n^2 < -4, then h(d*n^2) = L(0,kronecker(d,.)) * n * Product_{p|n, p prime} (1 - kronecker(d,p)/p). This is a combination of Theorem 7.24 in "Primes of the form x^2+ny^2" by Cox and the Dirichlet class number formula. Here L(0,kronecker(-11,.)) = 1.
%D A395772 D. A. Cox, Primes of the form x^2+ny^2, Wiley, New York, 1989, p. 146.
%H A395772 Jianing Song, <a href="/A395772/b395772.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%F A395772 Multiplicative with a(11^e) = 11^e, a(p^e) = p^(e-1)*(p-1) if p == 1, 3, 4, 5, 9 (mod 11) and a(p^e) = p^(e-1)*(p+1) if p == 2, 6, 7, 8, 10 (mod 11).
%e A395772 Given L(0,kronecker(-11,.)) = 1, we have: h(-11*1^2) = a(1) = 1, h(-11*2^2) = a(2) = 3, h(-11*3^2) = a(3) = 2, h(-11*4^2) = a(4) = 6, ...
%o A395772 (PARI) a(n,{d=-11}) = my(f=factor(n)[,1]~, w=#f); n * prod(i=1, w, 1 - kronecker(d,f[i])/f[i])
%Y A395772 A011582 is the corresponding Dirichlet character.
%Y A395772 Cf. for fundamental discriminants -3..-24: A227128, A395768, A395771, A395769, this sequence, A395773, A395774, A395775, A395776, A395777.
%K A395772 nonn,easy,mult,new
%O A395772 1,2
%A A395772 _Jianing Song_, May 05 2026
